text=:Category: Varia%0a:Expansion: Immersion%0a:Author: VikramM%0a:Original: [[Articles.LearningANewLanguage|LearningANewLanguage]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.leah_w|leah_w]]%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 07.05.2021 - 13:02%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-004219-406340#%0a* [-10.05.2021 - 17:42-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-004219-406340#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI came across a study from Georgetown University Medical Center on how the brain learns and processes a new language. The study compared how different regions of the brain were used in language learning through a traditional method versus an immersion-style method relative to regions of the brain used while speaking a native language. %0a%0aThe organizers of the study fabricated a small language to teach the participants and gave two groups with either classroom or immersion style instruction. The findings were that even though both groups were able to learn the language, the brain activity of the group that went through immersion style learning was more similar than the activity of those who received traditional teaching to brain activity when speaking a native language or first language. %0a%0aSource: https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2012/03/120328172212.htm%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
